column43: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column169: On December 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallond drum of printing ink was damaged and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Coastal Environmental Solutions (CES) to remediate the impacted site. CES personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the ink-impacted trailer floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon overpack and all impacted waste and absorbents collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon pail.

Pkg missing required markings for shipment containing hazardous contents. 1 x 24 oz. bottle of Hand Sanitizer 70% has a Flash point of 25-27 C (77-80.6 F) and typically ships as "Ltd Qty".  Loose and missing trigger spray heads of non-hazardous liquid contents allowed liquid to leak wetting and damaging the contents and carton. Excessive weight of the contents and weakening from the leaked liquid caused the corner of the carton to rip and glue to fail on the closure tape.

Both jerricans are being held at the location, awaiting disposition requests from the shipper.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 15-gallon drum containing hazardous product, Nalco Stabrex#ST70. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor in a 2'x2' area as a result of improper loading/inadequate preparation for transportation. The contractor used sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the release and applied oil dry to clean-up the spill. The damaged drum was overpacked into one 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. The neutralized and impacted oil dry was containerized into a separate 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste generated from the spill response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.
